du and the Everest region from a hike of several days to a 45-minute flight, the airstrip made a rapid increase in tourism possible. Beginning with his impressions of Sherpa society in pre-tourist days, Fisher traces the trajectory of contemporary Sherpa society reeling under the impact of modern education and mass tourism, and assesses the Sherpa's concerns for their future and how they believe these problems should be and eventually will be resolved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEducationxNepalxSolukhumbū. 0aEducationzNepalzSolukhumbū. 0aEducationzNepalzSolukhumbū. 0aSherpa (Nepalese people) 0aSherpa (Nepalese people). 0aSherpa (Peuple du Népal). 0aTourismxNepalxSolukhumbū. 0aTourismzNepalzSolukhumbū. 0aTourismzNepalzSolukhumbū. 0aTourismexNépalxSolukhumbū. 0aÉducationxNépalxSolukhumbū. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520909946423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520909946.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles